The Fragility of a Flat World
The world is flat!
As columnist Thomas Friedman put it, he chose this highly provocative title for his best-selling book to make people aware of the astonishing impact technology has had on the world economy.
The distance is shortening.
Geographic barriers can no longer provide protection so easily.
Manufacturing workers and high-tech professionals in Europe and the United States have all had to face the challenges of global competition.
When Western consumers call local companies, the employees they speak to are likely to be far away in India.
Skeptics have pointed out the limitations of Friedman's metaphor.
As someone said, the world is not flat, but rather "uneven and bumpy."
The topographic map of global economic activity shows peaks of prosperity and valleys of scarcity.
Moreover, distance has far from lost its significance.
Even neighboring countries with relatively low tariff barriers, such as Canada and the United States, have significantly more domestic trade than cross-border trade.
Seattle and Vancouver are geographically close, yet Vancouver's trade with the more distant Toronto is significantly higher than its trade with the nearby Seattle.
Despite such criticisms, Friedman presented an important point.
Globalization can be defined as the interdependence between different continents, a phenomenon as old as human history itself. It has witnessed the migration of races and religions, as well as the trade along the ancient Silk Road between medieval Europe and Asia.
But today's globalization is different; it is developing faster and more deeply than ever before.
After the first transatlantic telegraph cable was laid in 1868, Europe and America could communicate with each other within just one minute.
In 1919, the economist John Maynard Keynes depicted British people living in London ordering goods from around the world by telephone, then sitting at home waiting for them to arrive in the afternoon.
But Keynes was a rare exception among wealthy British people.
Today, hundreds of millions of people around the world can buy products from all over the world at their local supermarkets.
Similarly, twenty years ago, instant global communication existed, but it was economically beyond the reach of most people.
Now, almost anyone can walk into an internet café and gain access to capabilities that were once available only to the government, multinational corporations, and a few individuals or organizations with substantial budgets.
The significant decline in computing, communication, and transportation costs has made technology increasingly accessible.
Just ten years ago, two-thirds of internet users were concentrated in the United States.
Today, the proportion of internet users in the United States accounts for less than a quarter of the global user base.
Knowledge is power, and today the number of people who have access to information has reached the highest level in human history.
Non-state entities now possess capabilities that were previously held only by the government.
The status of the nation-state as a principal actor in world politics will not change in the near future, but it must learn to share this vast stage with a growing number of participants, including organizations such as the Oxford Committee for Famine Relief, celebrities like Bono, and transnational terrorist networks such as Al-Qaeda.
But this process of flattening is reversible.
Similar situations have occurred before.
The world economy was highly integrated in 1914, but during the following 30 years, economic interdependence among countries continuously declined.
It was not until 1970 that the global economy recovered to the level of integration it had previously experienced, although it was still heavily divided by the Iron Curtain at that time.
World War I served as the catalyst for the reversal, and during the two World Wars and one global Cold War, people witnessed a decline in economic globalization and an increase in military globalization.
This reflects deeper issues caused by the uneven development of the economy in the 19th century.
Politics failed to adapt to economic development, resulting in abnormal ideologies—fascism and communism—reaching their peak. This pathological concept of development caused the fragmentation of both nations and the world.
After World War II, the welfare state system in the West provided a safety net for those affected by economic changes, encouraging them to accept the benefits brought about by international economic interdependence.
Some analysts believe that China's role today is similar to that of Germany in the 20th century.
They are rising powers troubled by domestic inequalities, continuously moving toward nationalism, challenging the dominant forces, and ultimately triggering world wars that reverse the progress of economic globalization.
Although the economies of the United States and China are highly interdependent today, weren't the economies of Britain and Germany just as interdependent before 1914?
But such reasoning is not complete.
After 1900, Germany's industrial production had surpassed that of Britain.
However, even if China maintains its current high growth rate, its economy is unlikely to catch up with that of the United States within at least 20 years.
What poses a greater threat to the flat world is the non-state and transnational forces unleashed by the spread of technology.
On September 11, 2001, the number of Americans killed by a non-state network in an unprovoked attack exceeded the number of Americans killed in the Japanese government's attack on Pearl Harbor in 1941.
I refer to this phenomenon as the privatization of war.
If such forces were to gain control of nuclear weapons and biological materials, the world would undergo a dramatic transformation.
At that time, it would become more difficult for people and goods to cross borders.
If these forces disrupt the oil exports from the Persian Gulf, which holds two-thirds of the world's oil reserves, a global economic downturn similar to that of the 1930s could further strengthen protectionist tendencies.
Technology and policy are the two major driving forces of globalization.
So far, policies have further reinforced the flattening effect of technology.
As the world's largest economic entity, the United States holds a leading position in promoting policies aimed at removing obstacles.
But the events described above might reverse this policy.
Some critics of globalization may be willing to see such a result.
But such an outcome, as we saw after 1914, would lead to the worst situations in two areas: the economic globalization of communication technologies and power would reverse, while the negative consequences of military and ecological globalization would become further entrenched—for example, war, terrorism, climate change, and the spread of infectious diseases.
If that is indeed the case, the flat world would become a desert.
